<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / International Company News: Toshiba, IBM in technology link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Toshiba of Japan, a leading manufacturer of notebook personal computers, has
licensed microprocessor chip technology from International Business Machines
in a breakthrough agreement in IBM's efforts to establish its PowerPC chip
as a new standard for the personal computer industry.
Under the agreement, Toshiba will purchase PowerPC chips from IBM for use in
future products. It also gains rights to develop derivative PowerPC chips
and to manufacture these chips for use in its own products.
The agreement is also understood to include 'very significant' monitory
elements. Toshiba has also licensed IBM's AIX computer operating system
software.
'Toshiba and IBM consider this PowerPC alliance an important strategic step
toward next-generation computer development,' said Mr Kunika Mizushima,
executive vice-president of Toshiba.
Intel, the world's largest chip maker, dominates the market for
microprocessors used in PCs. About 90 per cent of all PCs sold contain
either Intel microprocessors or chips designed to emulate Intel's
technology.
IBM, together with Motorola and Apple Computer, are, however, attempting to
establish their jointly-developed PowerPC chips as a new industry standard.
Apple introduced its first PowerPC products earlier this year. IBM said
recently it had delayed introduction of PowerPC PCs until next year,
although the company already sells work-stations and multiprocessor
computers based on PowerPC chips.
Toshiba is the first of the world's leading PC manufacturers outside the
original PowerPC alliance to adopt PowerPC for use in future products,
making it a valuable ally for IBM.
</TEXT>
