<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / International Company News: UBS claims Ebner seeks control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Union Bank of Switzerland, the country's largest bank, last night said it
had strong reason to believe that a concert party was being formed to
acquire control of the bank on the cheap. That is why the bank earlier
yesterday proposed the conversion of all its registered shares into bearer
shares, thereby diluting their voting power.
UBS made clear that it believed Mr Martin Ebner's BZ banking group was
behind the effort to gain control. BK Vision, an investment company
controlled by BZ, is UBS's largest shareholder, and has built up an 18 per
cent stake in the registered shares worth about SFr1.2bn (Dollars 930m). The
UBS move would considerably dilute the voting power of this class of shares.
The registered shares have a par value of SFr20. In effect, they have five
times the voting power of SFr100 bearer shares.
Mr Ulrich Grete, UBS deputy chief executive, said officials of BK Vision had
met bank directors recently and indicated they wanted to win enough support
from shareholders to make significant alterations to the board of the
directors and orient the bank's strategy to maximise return on equity.
The bank said the registered shares were created in 1975 to prevent foreign
control of the bank. At the time, money from the Middle East was pouring
into Swiss securities. 'It is evident that the registered shares with
restricted transferability are today used by some shareholders to get an
influence on UBS's strategy which is far beyond their financial
involvement'.
It said the spread between the recent prices of the registered shares and
bearer shares had 'resulted in complaints by large private and institutional
investors'. Mr Ebner said the UBS move to dilute registered shareholders'
voting rights appeared to be a serious attack on Swiss securities law. He
was confident it would not succeed.
At yesterday's closing prices, the registered shares were at a 34 per cent
premium to the bearer shares.
BK Vision has had several skirmishes with UBS in the past two years. Last
week, the Zurich commercial court ruled in favour of a BK suit claiming that
UBS had illegally violated shareholder rights by creating pools of capital
that could be used at the board's discretion for acquisitions or convertible
bond issues.
Earlier this year, a BK motion to the UBS annual meeting proposing a cut in
board membership from 22 to a maximum of nine attracted about 40 per cent of
the votes.
A year ago, BK complained about the bank's decision to sack Mr Christoph
Blocher, a BK ally, from the board.
Two weeks ago it criticised the bank for becoming too dependent on volatile
securities trading activity for its profits.
</TEXT>
