<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / International Company News: USAir to pass payout on
preferred stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The financial troubles of USAir, the loss-making US airline in which British
Airways owns a 24.6 per cent stake, deepened yesterday with the announcement
that it would pass the quarterly dividend on two classes of its preference
stock.
The decision would cost BA about Dollars 25m in a full year. It would cost
Mr Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway investment group, another large
investor, about Dollars 33m.
The move sent BA shares tumbling in London yesterday with the shares losing
16p, more than 4 per cent, to close at 348p. BA shares have fallen by just
over 6 per cent during the last two days.
The announcement, which raises further concern about the financial health of
USAir, prompted fears that BA would have to carry out its threat to write
off all or part of its Dollars 400.7m investment in the troubled US carrier.
Earlier this month, it suffered its fifth fatal accident in five years with
the crash of a passenger airliner outside Pittsburgh, killing 132 people.
However, BA remains confident its partnership with USAir will this year
achieve Pounds 70m-worth (Dollars 110.6m) in gains from added revenues and
savings from its combined operations with the US carrier. BA said it had
this year received half the annual Dollars 25m in dividends due on its
preferred shares.
However, Mr Chris Avery, the London-based aviation analyst at Paribas, said
the announcement 'is more evidence of the very deep difficulties facing
USAir'. An increasing number of City analysts expect the US carrier to file
for US Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, although the airline is not facing
an immediate liquidity crisis.
The decision is seen as a signal of USAir's willingness to share sacrifices
with its unions, from which it is seeking wage concessions.
USAir's shares dropped Dollars 1 to close at Dollars 4.
</TEXT>
