<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / International Company News: UBS acts to curb Ebner's voting
power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Union Bank of Switzerland, the country's largest bank, is proposing to
convert all its registered shares into bearer shares in a thinly disguised
attack on Mr Martin Ebner's BZ banking group.
BK Vision, an investment company controlled by BZ, is UBS's largest
shareholder, and has built up an 18 per cent stake in the registered shares
worth about SFr1.2bn (Dollars 930m). The UBS move will considerably dilute
the voting power of this class of shares.
The registered shares have a par value of SFr20, thus giving an investment
in them five times the voting power of the same investment in the SFr100
bearer shares. The bank said its move was to prevent single holders of
registered shares, representing a minority of the share capital, from
getting 'excessive influence'.
UBS is proposing to reduce both classes of shares to a common SFr10 par
value, thereby equalising their voting power, and to eliminate restrictions
on foreigners voting.
The bank said the registered shares were created in 1975 to prevent foreign
control of the bank. It said the spread between the recent prices of the
registered shares and bearer shares had 'resulted in complaints by large
private and institutional investors'.
Mr Ebner said yesterday that the UBS move to dilute registered shareholders'
voting rights appeared to be a serious attack on Swiss securities law. He
was confident it would not succeed.
At yesterday's closing prices, the registered were at a 34 per cent premium
to the bearers.
BK Vision has had several skirmishes with UBS. Last week, the Zurich
commercial court ruled in favour of BK's claim that UBS had illegally
violated shareholder rights by creating pools of capital that could be used
at the board's discretion for acquisitions or convertible bond issues.
</TEXT>
