<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / IMF offers Dollars 360m to support Ukraine reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Monetary Fund agreed yesterday to provide Ukraine with
Dollars 360m (Pounds 227.8m) in financial support and held out the prospect
of further funding, as long as the Kiev government introduces economic
reforms.
Mr Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, said the loan, from the
IMF's systemic transformation facility to help former communist countries,
had 'all the potential to be the long awaited breakthrough' in bringing
order to Ukraine's economy.
But for it to succeed, Kiev would have to implement a 'strong package of
measures upfront' to restructure the economy and would need substantial
international financial support.
The IMF managing director said the agreement with Ukraine was a 'strong
first step' in the direction of economic reform. It involved a comprehensive
programme including price and exchange-rate stabilisation, a 'major effort'
to reduce the budget deficit, continuation of a tight monetary policy, a
pick-up in privatisation and restructuring of Ukraine's welfare system to
protect the most vulnerable groups.
The Dollars 360m will be handed to Ukraine once the programme has been
approved by the IMF board, probably next month. Mr Camdessus said
'considerably more assistance' would be available from the IMF in 1995 with
the Fund expecting to negotiate a stand-by credit agreement with Kiev early
next year.
However, IMF support would not be enough, Mr Camdessus said. He called on
other countries to pledge support to Ukraine during next week's annual
meetings of the IMF and World Bank in Madrid. This was an 'opportunity not
to be missed', he said.
But it is unclear how far other countries will take up Mr Camdessus's
suggestion. A Ukraine official said that Kiev is hoping for Dollars 1.5bn
from the industrialised countries as part of Dollars 4bn in support over two
years that was discussed by the Group of Seven leading industrial countries
at the July economic summit.
IMF reports, Page 7
Ukraine's blueprint, Page 18
