<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Insurers and watchdog at odds over pension sales
compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The City's chief regulator and the life insurance industry are deadlocked
over how to compensate people who could lose money from the mis-selling of
personal pensions.
The discord is a sign of the gulf between the Securities and Investments
Board and the life industry, which has become increasingly defensive after
public criticism of its practices.
The industry is refusing to set up a voluntary scheme to deal with
compensation claims for pension transfers - which some regulators now
believe could total Pounds 500m. Instead, cases will be handled within
existing compensation arrangements.
Details of how life companies should identify and compensate those who may
lose out because they took poor advice to opt or transfer out of an
occupational scheme will be published in an SIB report next month.
The report is also expected to confirm findings from a pilot study last
year, suggesting that up to a third of the 500,000 or more total pension
transfers since 1988 could have been based on poor advice.
The existing Investors Compensation Scheme, operated by the SIB together
with the industry, acts as a safety net for those entitled to redress who
find that the adviser responsible for their plight has ceased to trade.
The government and the regulator wanted separate arrangements for pension
transfers, to avoid the risk that they would swamp the current scheme.
Compensation claims in a pension transfer case go first to the life company
or independent financial adviser which mis-sold the pension. The ombudsman
for the Personal Investment Authority, the new regulator to protect the
private investor, will probably intervene in any dispute.
For the life industry, the most sensitive compensation issue is paying
claims against independent advisers who have gone out of business. Such
cases will now be handled by the ICS. A special unit is be set up within the
PIA to deal with inquiries from customers of such firms.
The scale of potential mis-selling indicated in next month's report is
likely to be a cause fresh of conflict between the SIB and the life
companies. Many life companies dismissed the pilot study, as it was based
entirely on files rather than talking to sales agents and customers. They
said the problem was one of record-keeping rather than of poor advice.
</TEXT>
