<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Management: Calling all those budding writers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A challenge to budding essayists is issued today by the Financial Times and
the UK's Management Consultancies Association.
It comes in the form of a jointly sponsored award aimed at encouraging
managers and management consultants to write a stimulating, original and
non-technical essay on a subject of current business interest.
Inspired by the government's white paper in May, the chosen topic for this
year's competition is 'Competitiveness - the key to success'.
The winning essay, say the sponsors, 'will be the one that is judged to add
focus to the debate by suggesting means, structural and substantial rather
than tactical and cosmetic, by which organisations can ensure greater
competitiveness through appropriate management of operations'.
Entries, which have to be submitted by December 1, must be between 2,000 and
3,000 words and written in English.
The winning author will receive a Pounds 3,000 cash prize and, with other
suitable essays, his or her work will appear in a booklet to be published by
the MCA in early 1995. The winning article will be considered for
publication in the FT.
For conditions of entry and an entry form contact FT-MCA Management Essay
Award, c/o Management Consultancies Association, 11 West Halkin Street,
London SW1X 8JL.
 ------------------------
The MCA has announced the second year of its sponsorship of a prize to
recognise and reward writers of management books.
The main prize of Pounds 5,000 is open to British writers of all ages, while
a special commendation (worth up to Pounds 2,000) will be made to the best
entry written by an author under 35.
Further information from Andrea Livingstone, 122 Fawnbrake Avenue, London
SE24 0BZ. Tel/fax: 071-738-6701
</TEXT>
