<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Public sector accounts shift call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leading professional accountancy body for public services yesterday
called for the establishment of a new body to set accounting standards in
the public sector.
Mr Martin Evans, technical director of the Chartered Institute of Public
Finance and Accountancy, said the new board could bring together public and
private practice.
He told the Government Accounting Service conference at the University of
Surrey that the last decade had seen a shift away from cash-based
public-sector accounting towards a more commercial system. Change in the
public sector had been prompted by compulsory competitive tendering, the
development of the internal market in the National Health Service, the Next
Steps programme for the civil service, the growth of housing associations
and structural changes in education.
He proposed that the new Public Sector Accounting Advisory Board would take
over the role fulfilled by the public-sector committee of the Accounting
Standards Board and other bodies. He said the government should become
involved and nominated 17 contributors to its costs - including the Treasury
and regulators such as the Housing Corporation.
</TEXT>
