<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Clarke's 1.5% solution dissolving fast: Robert Taylor
explains why it is proving hard to keep deals below the government's target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first results of the New Earnings Survey suggest it is increasingly
difficult for any government to control or even influence the level of pay
settlements in the economy.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, loses no opportunity in driving home his
message that he intends to enforce a stiff public-sector pay curb of 1.5 per
cent for the next three years. But the labour market is not the same as it
was in the 1960s and 1970s when successive governments ran incomes policies
from the centre with at least some success in ensuring pay restraint.
The demise of much national wage bargaining in the private sector in recent
years and the government's active encouragement of decentralisation and
efficiency-related pay in the public sector has ensured that an increasing
amount of wage bargaining is carried out at local level which is more
sensitive to market pressures.
'The survey this year shows there is an enormous amount of wage drift in the
economy,' said Mr Chris Trinder, research director of the independent Public
Finance Foundation.
It also suggests that those in work have been able to more than hold their
own in the relative level of their pay as they have benefited from survival
in a more flexible and insecure labour market where companies have cut
staffing levels.
Holding the line in the public sector is therefore going to be difficult as
the economic recovery gathers pace. Incomes Data Services, the independent
analyst, in its forecasts for 1995 believes most deals in the private sector
will range from between 3 per cent to 4.5 per cent.
'Higher levels of output and increased profitability will increase
employees' expectations in addition to whatever happens to inflation,' said
Mr Alistair Hatchett, editor of Incomes Data Report.
This could make it even harder for the government to keep the lid on
public-sector pay costs. Rises are still running almost neck and neck with
the private sector in spite of government policy and the first signs of
private-sector revival.
A number of public sector unions, particularly Unison with its large
membership in local government, will be able to draw arguments from the
earnings data to sustain their efforts to secure a substantial pay rise in
that sector.
Others may find it harder to whip up popular backing for their pay campaigns
 -not least the Royal College of Nursing, which is trying to convince the
review body covering nurses' earnings that they deserve a pay rise of at
least 8 per cent.
The survey evidence also looks set to fuel the debate inside the Labour
party on the introduction of a national minimum wage - there is likely to be
a fierce argument on this at its conference next week.
The Public Finance Foundation calculated yesterday that the lowest-paid 10
per cent of workers would need a minimum wage of Pounds 4.15 an hour to
ensure it is half the male median earnings, the target many in the Labour
party would like to set.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
