<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Public-sector rises exceed guidelines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many of those employed in Britain's public sector continue to enjoy pay
rises well above the government's own wage guidelines and the monthly pay
index.
This is the surprising but firm conclusion to be drawn from the detailed
evidence in the first instalment of this year's New Earnings Survey
published by the Department of Employment yesterday.
But the picture is highly diverse, with winners and losers in both the
public and private-sector pay league tables.
The biggest boost to pay in the public sector in the year to April was for
women employed full-time in the BBC - their average earnings climbed by 12.2
per cent to Pounds 500.80 for a 37-hour week. They were followed by
full-time women secretaries and typists in the civil service, with a 7.5 per
cent rise in earnings to Pounds 257.40 for a 37-hour week.
The highest percentage rises among full-time male employees in the public
sector were those employed as scientific officers in the civil service with
a 6.8 per cent increase to Pounds 451.30 for a 37.5-hour week.
They were followed by female nurses and midwives who had a 6.2 per cent rise
in average earnings to Pounds 305.40 for a 38-hour working week. Ambulance
workers were next with a 6.1 per cent rise to Pounds 313.20 for a massive
49.7-hour week, including 5.4 hours of overtime.
Male teachers in England and Wales secured 3.4 per cent rises to an average
Pounds 454.70 for a 30.4-hour working week while their female colleagues had
3.8 per cent rises to Pounds 395.30 for a 30.1-hour week.
Men employed in the higher and middle grades of the civil service had 3.7
per cent rises to Pounds 417.90 for a 38.9-hour working week but their
female colleagues secured 3.4 per cent in earnings to Pounds 344.30 for a
38.4-hour working week.
There have been some losers in the public sector. Male police had average
pay rises of only 0.3 per cent to Pounds 446.80 for a 42-hour week while
firefighters had 1.1 per cent, taking them to an average Pounds 344.60 for a
43.6-hour week. Both of those groups have their pay linked to the earnings
of others.
Male manual workers in local government in England and Wales had only a 1.8
per cent earnings rise to Pounds 241 for 47.3 hours a week while in Scotland
the comparable group secured a 1.2 per cent improvement to Pounds 248.30 for
a 50.1-hour working week. Low earnings increases were also recorded for
academics (up 1.2 per cent for men and 2.6 per cent for women).
In the private sector the picture is even more diverse, with some
substantial earnings increases in a number of industries and services.
The largest earnings boost was recorded among males in the managerial and
professional group at British Telecommunications, with a 22.6 per cent
increase taking their pre-tax pay to Pounds 702.00 for a 41.6-hour working
week.
Substantial improvements were also recorded for men in British Gas (10.1 per
cent), the car industry (13.0 per cent), ceramics (16.6 per cent) and
general printing in England and Wales.
The survey also reveals widespread regional pay differences.
New Earnings Survey 1994, Part A. HMSO. Pounds 13.00.
