<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / ICL formalises link with Virgin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Virgin Group, which last year announced it was entering the personal
computer market, has formalised an agreement with ICL, the UK-based computer
company, to manufacture its range of desktop and notebook computers.
The deal, which includes joint marketing and distribution, is thought to be
worth about Pounds 5m to ICL in the first year and at least double that in
subsequent years.
The Virgin computers will be slanted towards the games and multimedia
markets and marketed through both Virgin and ICL channels. ICL will also
have the right to use the Virgin name on some equipment.
The UK company, in which Fujitsu of Japan has a majority stake, believes the
Virgin name may help it penetrate the home-office and small-office market in
mainland Europe.
ICL's own-brand computers are chiefly aimed at business markets.
ICL has been assembling up to 1,000 Virgin computers a month on an informal
basis since the leisure group entered the market. Virgin distributes its PC
products through its shops, mail catalogues and a small distribution
network.
