<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Walker's QC accuses two 'evil directors'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, the former chairman of the Brent Walker property and
leisure group who is accused of illegal profit-boosting, may have been taken
advantage of by two 'evil' directors of the company's film division, the Old
Bailey was told yesterday.
In his closing speech to the jury, Mr Colin Nicholls, QC for Mr Walker, said
he still denied prosecution claims that the company's profits had been
fraudulently inflated by Pounds 19m.
However, it was possible that Mr John Quested and Mr Donald Anderson, the
former managing director and finance director of the Brent Walker film
subsidiary, had 'taken advantage' of Mr Walker's trust and friendship for
their own purposes.
Mr Walker and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, a former Brent Walker finance director,
deny charges of theft, false accounting and conspiring to falsify the Brent
Walker accounts. Mr Quested and Mr Anderson have been named by the
prosecution as co-conspirators.
Mr Nicholls said that Mr Quested, the former managing director of the film
division, was 'well in evidence' at the time the fraud was supposed to have
taken place.
He was 'in the background, but you can do a lot in the background'. His
conduct was 'highly suspect', added Mr Nicholls. Mr Quested was a 'practised
forger' and the prosecution had accepted that some documents in the case
might have been forged by him.
It could be that in letting staff look after the detailed work of deals, Mr
Walker had trusted them too much. During the period when the fraud was
alleged to have occurred, 'these two evil men' had been left to do what they
wanted, Mr Nicholls suggested. 'Is the fault of Mr Walker that he trusted
his friends too much? That may be one of the reasons why he is here now,' Mr
Nicholls said. The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
