<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Tec to be warned over payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
South Thames Training and Enterprise Council is expected to be warned next
week that it is in breach of its contract and that it must take urgent
remedial action in its financial monitoring systems by the end of the year.
The action is the first taken by the Department of Employment against any of
the 82 Tecs which administer government training in England and Wales,
although it is understood that the department is in discussion with others
over similar problems.
Tecs receive about Pounds 2bn in public funds to deliver programmes
including Youth Training and Training for Work, a scheme for unemployed
adults.
The problem at South Thames concerns lack of adequate controls over payments
to providers of training. There is understood to be no question of
dishonesty involving anyone at the Tec.
In August the Tec's finance director resigned after its non-executive board
expressed concerns over accountancy matters. Mr Michael Hanson, the chief
executive, who was admired for his vision of training and enterprise in the
inner-city area, has also resigned.
It is understood that the Tec's auditors are awaiting details of the breach
notice before deciding whether to qualify its accounts.
Tecs have had problems in accounting fully for the money they spend with the
private and public-sector bodies with which they contract to provide
training.
Mr Tim Hoult, chairman of South Thames Tec, said yesterday: 'The breach
notice is not a surprise to us. We have a remedial action plan and I am
quietly confident that the action we are taking will result in the breach
notice being lifted.'
</TEXT>
