FT  30 SEP 94 / Dealers warn on new-car figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The retail motor trade last night renewed its call for car manufacturers to
stop inflating the new-car market by pre-registering cars for which there
were no actual buyers, John Griffiths writes.
Mr Derek Lindop, president of the Retail Motor Industry Federation, said
that artificially boosting the market in order to keep production lines
flowing was continuing to send the 'wrong signals' to government about the
strength of the economic recovery.
He told the institute's annual dinner, attended by Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade secretary, that the practice of pre-registration - in which cars are
later sold as 'used' but with only nominal mileage - was undermining the
viability of the 7,000 franchised dealers.
The year-on-year sales increase of nearly 10 per cent shown by the
statistics greatly overstated underlying growth. This was closer to 4 per
cent.
