<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Universities plan business links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
University vice-chancellors announced yesterday that they would create a new
post of chief executive to help build links between higher education and the
private sector.
Dr Kenneth Edwards, chairman of the Committee of Vice-Chancellors and
Principals, which ended its annual conference in Birmingham yesterday, said:
'Universities need to become more entrepreneurial than ever. They must find
more public and private investment to restructure and re-equip for new
teaching and learning techniques.'
He added that universities played 'a key role in supporting economic
regeneration', and that they were bound to become 'even more central to
civic life' as more people entered higher education.
The committee had previously resisted creating a chief executive in favour
of a more loose organisation.
Dr Edwards - the vice-chancellor of Leicester University - also claimed that
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, would need to introduce new
funding arrangements.
Mrs Shephard had told the committee: 'Universities have achieved
considerable success in the past decade or so. Now that we are in a period
of consolidation, we must not miss the chance to make sure our quality
systems are equally good.'
But the committee said: 'Those achievements will be short-lived if
government does not ensure that the system is adequately funded.'
Vice-chancellors said the system of subsidised loans to cover student living
costs should be reformed immediately. Repayments should be tied to the
National Insurance system, linking them closer to graduates' incomes and
reducing collection costs.
But the Department for Education ruled out any change to the loans system
until 1997 at the earliest.
The committee also agreed to review the admissions system to take into
account the wider range of entry qualifications now being offered such as
General National Vocational Qualifications.
</TEXT>
