FT  30 SEP 94 / N Korea talks disappoint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US negotiators admitted last night that little progress had been made in the
latest round of high-level talks with North Korea on Pyongyang's suspect
nuclear programme, writes Frances Williams in Geneva.
Mr Robert Gallucci, chief US negotiator, and Mr Kang Sok-ju, North Korea's
first deputy foreign minister, plan to meet again on Tuesday, according to
North Korean officials. Mr Gallucci said only that he would meet Mr Kang
again next week.
Technical experts will stay in Geneva to continue the week-long talks, which
centre on a US offer to help North Korea switch from graphite-moderated to
light-water reactors, which produce less plutonium. Among the sticking
points are a North Korean demand for hefty compensation to abandon its
current reactor programme.
