<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / OECD in race against time to fill top job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The clock ran out last night on the tenure of Mr Jean-Claude Paye as
secretary general of the 25-nation Organisation for Economic Co-operation
and Development (OECD) without member countries' ambassadors being able to
agree that either he or a rival US-backed Canadian candidate should be named
to a full new term.
After eight hours of talks yesterday and on Wednesday failed to break the
deadlock - essentially between France and the US - OECD envoys headed into a
further late-night meeting, aimed simply at agreeing on a caretaker head of
the organisation.
Mr Paye, whose second five-year term came to an end at midnight, has two
deputies - one American and one Swede - who could fill that caretaker role,
until such time as the international economic think-tank chooses to restart
the competition for its top job.
But France has been determined to keep Mr Paye on, even on an interim basis,
on the ground that the French incumbent had majority support within the
organisation's 25 members, who are mainly European.
Late yesterday, however, the US was still adamant that it would not accept
Mr Paye staying on, even as a temporary caretaker, arguing that 10 years was
enough and that it was time for the organisation to have a non-European
head.
It has strongly backed Mr Donald Johnston, a former Canadian minister, who
also has the support of his own government and some other non-European
countries such as Australia and New Zealand.
Short of a major climb-down by Paris or Washington, it is increasingly
likely that both Mr Paye and Mr Johnston will have to withdraw, having
effectively cancelled each other out. This would leave Lord Lawson, former
UK chancellor of the exchequer, as the only declared candidate left in the
field. But since his support was largely confined to the UK government,
others would probably throw their hats into the ring.
Meanwhile, one side-effect of the OECD impasse was that the Paris-based
International Energy Agency yesterday named a new director, but only on an
acting basis.
Mr John Ferriter is to take over as interim executive director of the IEA
from Ms Helga Steeg, who is retiring after 10 years at the agency. The IEA
seeks to co-ordinate energy policy among member countries, which largely
overlap with the OECD. Some of them, notably France and the US, appear to be
using the definitive choice of an IEA director as a weapon in the battle
over the secretary-generalship of the older and more prestigious OECD.
</TEXT>
