<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Grenade attack kills four Haitians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES HARDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A grenade attack on a pro-democracy march in Port-au-Prince yesterday -
which left at least four dead and up to 40 injured - threatened to
destabilise the Haitian capital on the eve of a huge demonstration expected
today.
It was not immediately clear who was responsible for the attack, the most
violent incident since US troops arrived in the country. It came after US
and Haitian authorities staged the symbolic return of elected mayor Evans
Paul to the Port-au-Prince town hall.
Mr Paul had been in hiding for nearly a year. People gathered in the
streets, chanting slogans demanding the arrest of Haiti's military leaders
and calling for the return of exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, who
is still in the US.
The celebration was thrown into chaos when the grenade was tossed into the
crowd. The incident, which was followed by another reported attack, this
time a shooting, set off a wave of looting.
The US army immediately stepped up its deployment, sending in Sheraton tanks
and Bradley armoured vehicles. Troops shot their way into a warehouse in an
attempt to secure the area.
Mr William Swing, US ambassador in Haiti, said that 'brutal acts of violence
are not totally unexpected. . . because the enemies of democracy will resort
to any ends and means to stop the democratic change process.'
Even before the attacks, tension was expected today as thousands of Haitians
are due to march through the streets of Port-au-Prince to show support for
Mr Aristide on the third anniversary of the coup that ousted him from
office.
The United Nations Security Council voted last night to lift fuel, trade and
arms sanctions against Haiti, beginning the morning after President Aristide
returns from exile. The vote was 13-0, with Russia and Brazil abstaining.
</TEXT>
